 women were seen as society's key agents of socialization. The AIU thus concluded that its boys' schools would never succeed in creating polished, westernized men so long as women remained uneducated, leading to the creation of schools for girls. Sciarcon shows how headmistresses acted not just as educators but also as models of modernity, trying to impart new moral and aesthetic norms onto students.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aGirlsxEducationzIraq. 0aGirls' schoolszIraqxHistory. 0aJewish day schoolszIraqxHistory. 4aArea Studies : Middle East Studies. 4aArea Studies : Ottoman Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aHistory : World History. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2017z978311149102840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438465869423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438465869/original  a978-3-11-149102-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles